<!-- cabbage-details.njk (UPDATED) -->

<section class="card">
  <h2>About Cabbage</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    A cool-season staple that rewards early timing and steady growth.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Cabbage thrives in cool weather and tolerates light frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate planning, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), cabbage success is mostly about runway: enough frost-free time to size up, plus enough seasonal heat to form a firm head before sustained cold or heat stress interrupts development.
  </p>

  <p>
    Cabbage works well across cold-climate regions because it establishes in cool conditions that would stall warm-season crops. The common failure mode in short seasons is not “instant frost kill”—it’s delayed growth that pushes heading into heat or into late-season slowdown with minimal buffer.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 8–10 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> 2–4 weeks before last frost (after hardening off)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 60–110 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light to moderate (quality risk rises with repeated hard freezes)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are practical ranges. Local exposure matters—especially wind, rapid temperature swings, and how quickly summer heat arrives.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Sensitivity & Temperature Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–70°F (13–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below 45°F (7°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress / bolting risk:</strong> Above ~80°F (27°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Light freeze tolerance:</strong> Often tolerates brief dips below 32°F (0°C) once established</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Established cabbage often tolerates a brief freeze at 32°F (0°C) without major damage, but repeated hard freezes can degrade outer leaves and reduce head quality.
    In short seasons, heat and growth interruptions are usually more limiting than a single light frost event.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Timing & Planting Window</h2>

  <p>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 normals, 50% probability), use your frost dates as boundaries and schedule transplants so cabbage builds size during cool weeks.
    This is deterministic planning: you’re fitting a maturity requirement inside a frost-defined season.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Start indoors ~8–10 weeks before your target transplant window, then transplant 2–4 weeks before last frost after hardening off.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Time sowing/transplants so heads form before sustained freezing; fall heading often improves in gradually cooling weather.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a> to calculate indoor start and transplant windows from your frost dates.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    If you want a clear reminder of what frost dates represent (and what they don’t), see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,400 GDD (base 50) depending on variety length (early vs storage types)</p>

  <p>
    Cabbage is a cool-season crop, but head formation still depends on accumulated seasonal heat. When seasonal heat is weak, development slows and maturity can drift later—reducing your buffer before the season boundary.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined model (frost boundary + heat budget), see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Cabbage is variety-dependent. Early types can fit tighter windows, while storage types need a longer runway.
    As a rough planning baseline, many cabbage crops need <strong>60–110 frost-free days</strong> from transplant to harvest, depending on variety and growing conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your frost-free window is short, cabbage can still be viable—but variety selection and early transplant timing become the deciding factors.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Often yes (especially early varieties, started indoors)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Can be without early varieties and on-time transplanting</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful for wind protection and steadier early growth (light cover), not for pushing through hard freezes</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Cabbage can tolerate light frost, but repeated hard freezes can damage outer leaves and reduce quality. For planning, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary and aim to form firm heads with buffer ahead of sustained cold.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Start indoors so you can transplant early and protect the cool-season window</li>
    <li>Choose early-heading varieties when your frost window is tight</li>
    <li>Prioritize steady growth (avoid drought stress and long stalls)</li>
    <li>Use microclimates: full sun + wind shelter to preserve effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, cabbage is viable when your frost-free window provides enough time and your seasonal heat budget provides enough GDD to reach heading with buffer.
    When buffer is thin, timing slips (late transplant, stalled early growth) are the main failure mode.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can cabbage survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Often, yes—established cabbage commonly tolerates light frost. For GrowByDate planning, use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary date and treat deeper, repeated freezes as a quality risk.
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my cabbage form a head?</h3>
  <p>
    Head formation often fails when growth is uneven—heat stress, drought, or long stalls early can prevent tight heading or cause loose heads.
  </p>

  <h3>Is cabbage better in spring or fall?</h3>
  <p>
    Both can work. Spring cabbage depends on early transplanting to beat heat. Fall cabbage often heads more consistently as temperatures cool—if planted early enough to size up before sustained freezing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use frost at 32°F (0°C) as the planning boundary (1991–2020 normals, 50% probability).</li>
    <li>Cabbage is usually limited by runway and growth interruptions, not immediate frost kill.</li>
    <li>Typical fit improves with indoor starts, early transplanting, and early varieties when seasons are tight.</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window (time) + seasonal heat budget (GDD) + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>
